publication_data.title: Illusory Truth Occurs Even with Incentives for Accuracy
publication_data.apa_reference: Brashier, N., & Rand, D. (2021). Illusory truth occurs even with incentives for accuracy.

study_data.study_comment: Reaction time is available in raw data, although there is no further information in the paper.

between_condition_details.name: Half of the participants learned that the experimenter would randomly choose one answer and assign a $1 bonus if it was correct
The other half received no monetary incentive

statementset_data.statement_text: The discoverer of the smallpox vaccination was Jenner.
The Cuban leader that Castro overthrew was Batista.
The brightest star in the sky excluding the sun is Sirius.
The author of "The Stranger" is Camus.
The rubber roller on a typewriter is called the bell.
The poet who originally wrote "Don Juan" was Frost.
The man most responsible for photographing the U.S. Civil War was Adams.
The land of the giants in "Gulliver's Travels" is Lilliput.
Unfrozen ground in an area of permafrost is called talik.
The tropical bird nicknamed "stinkbird" is the hoatzin.
Young alpacas are called crias.
The element named for a Scandinavian city is thulium.
Peddlers who sell religious books are costermongers.
A fortnight in the Hindu lunar calendar is a pahar.
The hobby of collecting postcards is phillumeny.
Depression following a nightmare is called oneirophrenia.
The cosmonaut who completed the first orbit of Earth was Gagarin.
The highest mountain in South America is Aconcagua.
The poet who wrote the line "into each life some rain must fall" was Longfellow.
An old number two wood in golf is a brassie.
The most popular pin-up girl of World War II was Harlow.
The twenty-first U.S. president was Garfield.
Angel Falls is located in Brazil.
The mountains separating Asia from Europe are the Himalayas.
The sport associated with Afghanistan is buzkashi.
The separation of bones without fracture is diastasis.
A plant that pales due to lack of sun is called etiolated.
The first name of children's author Dr. Seuss was Theodor.
The neurological term for lack of motivation is anosmia.
The capital city of Fiji is Apia.
Loss of eyelashes or eyebrows is koilonychia.
The smallest insect species is the adelgid.
